<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<handout>
  <title>Worksheet 10.2, The Steady‑State Vector and Page Rank</title>

  <ul marker="">

    <!-- Problem 1 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(1) &#160; A set of web pages link to each other according to the diagram below.</p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-tikz-pagerank">
        <caption>A figure of a transition diagram representing the connections between 5 web pages. </caption>
            <image width="40%" xml:id="pagerank">
            <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture} [node distance=5mm]<!-- [>=Stealth, node distance=34mm, thick] -->
        \tikzstyle{state}=[circle, draw, minimum size=18pt, inner sep=0pt]
        % Nodes at triangle vertices
        \node[state] (X) at (0, 0) {X};
        \node[state] (V) at (0, 2) {V};
        \node[state] (W) at (2, 2) {W};
        \node[state] (Y) at (4, 2){Y};
        \node[state] (Z) at (4, 0){Z};

        % Edges with probabilities
        \path[->]
            (X) edge[] (V)
            (V) edge[] (W)
            (W) edge[] (V)
            (W) edge[] (X)
            (X) edge[] (W)
            (W) edge[] (Y)
            (Y) edge[] (Z);
        \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
          <p>Create the transition matrix <m>P</m> for this web.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Construct the Google matrix <m>G</m> for this web.
            Use damping factor <m>p = 0.85</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            During an exam, to determine the page ranks of each page in the web
            you would be given the steady‑state vector of <m>G</m>.
            Since you are not taking an exam right now, compute the steady‑state
            vector and page ranks of each page on the web. You may use software.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        Hint: For a web with only two pages that are linked to each other,
        the steady state can be computed in MATLAB or Octave using:
      </p>

      <ul marker = "">
        <li><p>Pstar=1/2*[0 1;1 0]</p></li>
        <li><p>K = 1/2*ones(2)</p></li>
        <li><p>p = 0.85</p></li>
        <li><p>G = p*Pstar + (1-p)*K</p></li>
        <li><p>G ∧ (100)</p></li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        There are many free online Octave compilers.
      </p>
    </li>
</ul>
<ul marker = "">

    <!-- Problem 2 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(2) &#160; Suppose <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are real numbers in the open interval <m>(0,1)</m>, and</p>

      <p>
        <me>
        A =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          p &amp; 1-q \\
          1-p &amp; q
        \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>

      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>Is <m>A</m> stochastic? Is <m>A</m> regular?</p></li>
        <li><p>By inspection, what is one eigenvalue of <m>A</m>?</p></li>
        <li><p>Compute the steady‑state vector of <m>A</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Compute <m>\lim_{n \to \infty} A^n</m>.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </li>

    <!-- Problem 3 -->
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(3) &#160; Consider the dynamical system <m>\vec{x}_k = A\vec{x}_{k-1}</m>,
      for <m>k = 1,2,3,\dots</m>, where</p>

      <p>
        <me>
        A =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          0.5 &amp; 0.25 &amp; 0.25 \\
          0.25 &amp; 0.5 &amp; 0.25 \\
          0.25 &amp; 0.25 &amp; 0.5
        \end{pmatrix},
        \quad
        \vec{x}_0 =
        \begin{pmatrix}
          1 \\ 0 \\ 0
        \end{pmatrix}.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        The eigenvalues of <m>A</m> are <m>1</m> and <m>\tfrac{1}{4}</m>.
        Analyze the long‑term behavior of the system.
        In particular, determine what <m>\vec{x}_k</m> tends to as <m>k \to \infty</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

  </ul>
</handout>